{"edits":[{"content":"The target's third forbidden case is self-defeating under std-crit-design clause (2) and the standard's honesty requirement. The forbidden case is: 'Experiment shows harness > SC by >= 0.03 at P(fragile) = 0.1 with critic precision-on-fragile = 0.4 < 0.5, refuting the precision > 0.5 threshold in the claim.' This forbidden case is designed to refute a precision > 0.5 threshold, but the claim's iff statement contains no precision > 0.5 threshold — it requires E[P(SC_right | C) - P(SC_right | !C)] > 0 (positive question-conditional net signal), which is a different quantity from precision-on-fragile. A critic with precision-on-fragile = 0.4 could still have positive net signal if its recall on right-majority questions is high enough, so observing harness > SC at precision = 0.4 would not actually refute the claim as stated. More critically, the target's own scope explicitly 'covers' regimes where 'critic positive-class precision exceeds 0.5 on fragile-majority questions,' meaning the proposal already restricts its domain to precision > 0.5. A forbidden case that falls outside the proposal's own stated scope (precision = 0.4 < 0.5) cannot serve as a genuine refutation — it tests a regime the proposal explicitly excludes. Under std-crit-design clause (2), forbidden cases must be 'concrete, measurable outcomes of running the proposed experiment that would refute the proposal had they obtained.' An outcome in an excluded regime cannot refute a proposal that never claimed coverage there. The forbidden case is thus vacuous: it cannot falsify the actual claim, rendering the proposal's falsification apparatus incomplete with respect to the precision boundary it purports to test. The target's third forbidden case is self-defeating under std-crit-design clause (2) and the standard's honesty requirement. The forbidden case is: 'Experiment shows harness > SC by >= 0.03 at P(fragile) = 0.1 with critic precision-on-fragile = 0.4 < 0.5, refuting the precision >